{{Coord|51.517972|-0.044360|source:wikimapia_region:GB_type:landmark_scale:5000|display=title}} [[File:Picture of Baptists College, Stepney courtesy of the Queen Mary University of London.png|thumb|Drawing of the Baptist College, the section to the far right being the only remaining evidence of the building]] [[File:Photograph of the front of the Baptist College chapel remains.jpg|thumb|A 2010 photograph showing the remains of the Chapel frontage]] '''The Baptist College, Stepney''', was opened in [[Stepney]] in the East End of London in 1810 by the [[Particular Baptists]]. Its buildings included rooms for tutors and students, a refectory, a library and a chapel. The college relocated to larger premises at [[Holford House]] in 1856 and became [[Regent's Park College, Oxford|Regent's Park College]].<ref name="Dissenting Academies">{{cite web|url=https://dissacad.english.qmul.ac.uk/sample1.php?*detail=achist&histid=25&acadid=183|title=Baptist College, Stepney (1810-1856) and Regent's Park College, London (1856-1927)|publisher=dissacad.english.qmul.ac.uk|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>
The only remaining structure is the largely-destroyed Baptist Academical Institution chapel. The building remained until it was damaged during [[World War 2]]; only three parts of the college estate remain.<ref name="WinfieldNigel">{{cite book|last=Winfield|first=Nigel|title=Stepping Stones: Community Farm Project in Stepney, East London|year=1986|publisher=British Association of Settlements and Social Action Centres|location=UK|isbn=0950345253|pages=32}}2</ref>
The site is currently part of the [[Stepney City Farm]]. [[Crossrail]] works are taking place there.<ref>[http://74f85f59f39b887b696f-ab656259048fb93837ecc0ecbcf0c557.r23.cf3.rackcdn.com/assets/library/document/0/original/0003-r-stepneygreen.pdf Structures at King John Street, Stepney Green, London E1 (Stepney College and Stepney Meeting, or Congregational Church)] Museum of London Archaeology Service</ref>
