'''Iceberg B-31''' is a large [[iceberg]] that formed in November 2013, when it separated from the [[Pine Island Glacier]]. B-31 is heading into the [[Antarctic ocean]], which may have possible repercusions for international shipping.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carlowicz|first1=Michael|title=Drifting with ice island B31|url=http://visibleearth.nasa.gov/view.php?id=83519|website=www.nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/22/world/asia/antarctic-iceberg/index.html|title=Iceberg is twice the size of Atlanta - CNN.com|first=By Brad Lendon|last=CNN|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1284243/watch-iceberg-six-times-of-manhattan-on-the-move-in-antarctic/|title=WATCH: Iceberg 6 times the size of Manhattan on the move in Antarctic|first=Nicole|last=Mortillaro|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyjoe.com/2014/04/22/news/city-sized-iceberg-drifting-into-southern-ocean/|title=City-Sized Iceberg Drifting Out to Sea|date=22 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref> Soon it would not be possible to track the iceberg as the winter darkness completely hides it. The ice island is 20 miles by 12 miles and 500 m of height. It was first observed by [[Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer]] (MODIS), an instrument on NASA's Terra and Aqua satellites of NASA.
