{{Infobox mountain | name = Squaw's Tit | photo = | photo_caption = | elevation_m = 2514 | elevation_ref = <ref name=peakfinder>{{cite peakfinder|title=Squaw's Tit|accessdate=2007-09-03|author=PeakFinder}}</ref> | prominence = | location = [[Alberta]], [[Canada]] | range = [[Fairholme Range]] | coordinates = {{coord|51|08|10|N|115|20|15|W|type:mountain_region:CA}} | topo = [[National Topographic System|NTS]] 82O/03 | first_ascent = | easiest_route = [[Scrambling|Scramble]] }}
'''Squaw's Tit''' is an outlier of Mount Charles Stewart in the [[Canadian Rockies]] of [[Alberta]]. It is located at Lat/Lon: 51.13°N, 115.33°W and is one of the most prominent landmarks in the vicinity of [[Canmore, Alberta]].<ref>http://dowclimbing.com/SquawsTit.html</ref>
"Squaw's Tit" is an unofficial name for the high point of a ridge that lies southwest of the [[Mount Charles Stewart]] summit and northwest of [[Mount Lady Macdonald]] near [[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]]. The peak owes its name to the resemblance it shares with a woman's upturned [[breast]]. Due to its [[politically incorrect]] name, it is unlikely to receive official status{{according to|date=January 2016}}, but is in common use.
Belonging to the [[Fairholme Range]] in [[Peter Lougheed Provincial Park|Kananaskis Provincial Park]], Squaw's Tit is located {{convert|4000|ft}} above the [[Bow River]] valley. It is {{convert|2|km}} northwest of Lady Macdonald, just east of the [[Banff National Park]] gates.
==Routes== The scrambling route is graded moderate but includes exposure and thus is strongly recommended that the ascent only be done in dry conditions. Follow the major drainage ditch behind Harvey Heights and stay close along the right (south) side of the ditch. Follow this up to the North West ridge all the way to the slabs just below the protruding summit nipple.
